The 3 Planetary Constraints

These are the environmental factors that quietly shape where civilizations appear.

1. Climate Stability

Most civilizations arose during the Holocene, the unusually stable climate period of the last ~11,700 years.

Stable climate allows:
	•	predictable harvests
	•	population growth
	•	permanent settlements
	•	surplus production

Without stability, societies remain mobile.

⸻

2. Geographic Connectivity

Civilizations flourish where travel and trade are feasible.

Examples:
	•	navigable rivers
	•	coastal seas
	•	steppe corridors
	•	fertile valleys

Connectivity allows:

trade
technology transfer
migration
information exchange

Too isolated → stagnation.
Too open → instability.

⸻

3. Domesticable Species

Civilization depends on species humans can domesticate.

Key examples:
	•	wheat
	•	barley
	•	rice
	•	maize
	•	cattle
	•	sheep
	•	horses

Some continents simply lacked suitable species.

That shaped the global development pattern.

⸻

Why These Three Matter

When these three align:

stable climate
+ connected geography
+ domesticable plants/animals

Civilization becomes much more likely.

That’s why early civilizations appear in similar zones:
	•	Nile
	•	Mesopotamia
	•	Indus
	•	Yellow River
	•	Mesoamerica

